The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, April 29: The country?s trade deficit jumped by a whopping 86 per cent to touch the $26.52-billion mark for the financial year ended March 31, 2005 from $14.27 billion in 2003-04. The 24.41 per cent increase in exports during the year could not match the 35.62 per cent surge in imports, which went up to $106 billion from $78.25 billion in the previous year.

 New Delhi, April 29: The infrastructure growth slowed down to 4.4 per cent during 2004-05 from 6.2 per cent in the previous financial year. This was mainly because of poor showing by the petroleum refining, coal and steel sectors.

 New Delhi, April 29: The finance ministry will reduce the paperwork for indirect taxes from May 1. The total number of periodic reports to be made by assessees to indirect tax authorities has been reduced from 133 to seven.

 Mumbai, April 29: General Motors Asia-Pacific has appointed Rajeev Chaba, chief operating officer, as president and managing director of General Motors India effective June 1 in place of Aditya Vij, who has been promoted and posted in GM?s Europe unit.

 New Delhi, April 29: The Orissa government and Korean giant Posco are fine-tuning the $10-billion deal to set up a steel plant in the state.




